Initial Areas of Investigation

  • How does the number of members/casuals change over the year/week/day?
  • How does the proportion of members to casuals change over the year/week/day?
  • What are the differences in trip length for the two groups?
  • What is the average speed of the two groups?
  • What are the differences in docking stations used by the two groups?
  • How does the popularity of stations compare against the number of docks at the station? (Are some stations running out of available bikes)
  • Are there any connections between particular high/low member/casual usage and location?
  • The regularity of trips(to/from work etc…)?
  • What are the differences in the group size during trips of the two groups?
  • Are there any dips in casual usage that align with a rise in member usage?

How does the number of members/casuals change over the year/week/day?

Yearly

mcWRTtime <- tibble("date" = as.Date(trips$s_at), "m_c" = trips$m_c)
mcWRTtime <- table(mcWRTtime)
mcWRTtime <- as.data.frame(mcWRTtime)
mcWRTtime$date <- as.Date(as.character(mcWRTtime$date), format="%Y-%m-%d")
mcWRTtime$m_c <- factor(mcWRTtime$m_c, levels = c("member", "casual"))

g_mcWRTtime <- mcWRTtime %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, Freq, color = m_c, group = m_c)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth() +
  labs(x = "2022/23",
       y = "Number or Rides Taken",
       title = "Usage Statistics of Customers",
       color = "Customer Type") +
  scale_x_date(breaks = "1 month", date_labels = "%B") +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("#ffa600", "#003f5c"), 
                      labels = c("Member", "Casual")) +
  theme_bw()

Fairly unsurprising pattern, peaks likely correlating with journeys to and from work, and with lunchtime. Bearing in mind the significant change in casual usage during the summer and at the weekends, I think it due diligence to break this down further dependent on those factors.

Summer - Winter Split

usageWRTtod_sw <- tibble("time_of_day" = hms::as_hms(ymd_hms(trips$s_at)),
                            "m_c" = trips$m_c, 
                            "wd" = wday(trips$s_at, week_start = 1),
                            "summer_winter" = 
                              ifelse(as.Date(trips$s_at,
                                             format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
                                     < as.Date("21/06/2022", 
                                               format = "%d/%m/%Y") |
                                       as.Date(trips$s_at, 
                                               format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ") 
                                     > as.Date("22/09/2022",
                                               format = "%d/%m/%Y"),
                                     "winter", "summer"))

usageWRTtod_sw$time_of_day <- usageWRTtod_sw$time_of_day %>%
  as.character(.) %>%
  strtrim(., width = 5) %>%
  paste0(., ":00") %>%
  hms::as_hms(.)

usageWRTtod_sw <- table(usageWRTtod_sw)
usageWRTtod_sw <- as.data.frame(usageWRTtod_sw)
usageWRTtod_sw$m_c <- factor(usageWRTtod_sw$m_c, 
                                levels = c("member", "casual"))

usageWRTtod_sw <- mutate(usageWRTtod_sw, 
                         mean_usage = ifelse(summer_winter == "summer", 
                                             Freq/93, Freq/272))

g_mcWRTtod_sw <- usageWRTtod_sw %>%
  ggplot(aes(time_of_day, mean_usage)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.1, aes(color = m_c, group = m_c)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", span = 0.1, aes(color = m_c, group = m_c)) +
  labs(x = "Hours of the Day",
       y = "Number or Rides Taken",
       title = "Hourly Usage Statistics of Customers",
       color = "Customer Type") +
  scale_x_time(breaks = minutes(seq(0,24,6)), 
               labels=c("12AM","6AM","12PM","6pm","12AM")) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("#ffa600", "#003f5c"), 
                      labels = c("Member", "Casual")) +
  facet_grid(summer_winter ~ wd, labeller = labeller(wd = c("1" = "Mon", "2" = "Tues",
                                            "3" = "Wed", "4" = "Thurs",
                                            "5" = "Fri", "6" = "Sat",
                                            "7" = "Sun"))) +
  theme_bw()

g_mcWRTtod_sw
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Reaffirms previous conclusions, and adds that there is significant usage around midnight Fri/Sat and Sat/Sun during the summer.

Overall takeaways:

  • Member usage consistently higher than Casual usage throughout the year but less so during the summer.
  • Member usage consistently higher than Casual usage throughout the week but less so during the weekend.
  • Busiest days however, actually arise from Casual usage.
  • Both user groups use the service more in the summer and less in the winter.
  • High variance of day to day usage statistics for casual users during the summer.
  • Low variance of day to day usage statistics for casual users during the winter.
  • Members have a fairly consistent fluctuation in their day to day usage.
  • Members use the service more during the the week, whereas casuals use the service more over the weekend.
  • In fact Casual usage overtakes member usage for weekends during the summer.
  • Usage has three peaks throughout the day, ~8:30 am, ~12:15pm, ~5:10pm.
  • However on weekends there are no such peaks, but instead generally high traffic between ~12pm to ~6pm.
  • Lowest traffic times fall between ~11pm to ~6am, with midday dips around 10am and again from ~8:30pm to ~11pm.

Conclusions Drawn:

  • A seasonal summer membership would likely meet the needs of a large proportion of casual users
  • A weekends only membership would likely meet the needs of a large proportion of casual users
  • Advertising and promotional offers will likely have the greatest effect during the summer, and even more specifically on summer weekends.
  • The service is far less enticing for Casual users during the winter, however, since there is still sizable usage among members, it might be worth investigating how to improve the service for during winter. In general surveys would be a good method of investigating this further and this goes outside the scope of this analysis, but I will examine whether electric or classic bikes hold any useful information later.
  • An off-peak membership with additional incentive for use would likely help smooth out the overall usage of the service as currently there are noticeable dips in usage, but this falls outside of the scope of this analysis as I am focusing on converting current casual users to members.

Caveats:

  • The service is finite, and I do not have access to information on what the total number of available bikes there are at any given time. Ergo, while for the scope of this analysis I am assuming that the usage statistics of one group has no effect on the usage statistics of the other; in actuality they very likely do affect each other to some degree.

The regularity of trips(to/from work etc…)?

freqtrips <- tibble("s_stn" = trips_wloc$s_stn, 
                    "e_stn" = trips_wloc$e_stn, 
                    "s_at" = hms::as_hms(ymd_hms(trips_wloc$s_at)), 
                    "e_at" = hms::as_hms(ymd_hms(trips_wloc$e_at)),
                    "m_c" = trips_wloc$m_c)

freqtrips$s_at <- hms::round_hms(freqtrips$s_at, digits = -4)
freqtrips$e_at <- hms::round_hms(freqtrips$e_at, digits = -4)

freqtrips$m_c <- factor(freqtrips$m_c, levels = c("member", "casual"))


freqtrips <- freqtrips %>%
  group_by(s_stn, e_stn, s_at, e_at, m_c) %>% 
  tally()

freqtrips <- arrange(freqtrips, desc(n))

i = 100

freq_label <- freqtrips %>%
  head(i) %>%
  group_by(m_c) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(freq = n(), n = mean(n))

g_freqtrips_100 <- freqtrips %>%
  head(., i) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = m_c, y = n, fill = m_c)) +
  geom_violin(scale = "count", trim = F, show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("Member", "Casual")) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(formatC((freq/i) * 100, format = "f", 
                                       digits = 0), "%")),
            size = 10, data = freq_label) +
  labs(x = "User Type", y = "Number of Times a Route Has Been Used",
       title = paste("Proportion of", as.character(i),
                     "Most Regular Routes Used by Each Customer Type"))

g_freqtrips_100

Not only do Members have a higher proportion of the 100 most used routes, but they also lay claim to the most used routes overall. While members have a significant percentage of the top most traveled routes there is still a sizable number of regular casual routes. Perhaps focused advertising along these regular routes would yield more efficient marketing; or an alternative cheaper membership option that only covered access to journeys around these areas would prove successful.

It should be noted that without access to specific user linked data, there is again no way of knowing if these trips are by one person or 1000 people; which greatly weakens the strength of the finding. However, with such promising early numbers, I’d argue that it warrants it’s own analysis, further to the current one.

This trend is repeated right up to the 10000 Most regular trips.

NB. There is some inaccuracy with this method due to the cut off being the 10,000th entry. The 10,001st entry and so on will likely have the same n value (number of times the route has been used) but isn’t included in the plot. As this is a first pass review and there is no obvious bias favouring one user type over the other, this error is acceptable.

Could be worth looking into the location of these high usage routes for each group; whether it matches up to the station usage analysis above, and if it could be used to narrow down a zone for which Casual users more regularly use the service and thus likely more favourable for conversion to Members.

Looking at bike type preference across the year and across the two user groups

What are the differences in the group size/composition during trips of the two groups?

group_analysis <- tibble("route_key" = paste(trips_wloc$s_stn, trips_wloc$e_stn, sep = "_"),
                         "s_at" = as_datetime(trips_wloc$s_at),
                         "e_at" = as_datetime(trips_wloc$e_at),
                         "m_c" = trips_wloc$m_c)

group_analysis <- group_analysis %>%
  arrange(s_at) %>%
  arrange(route_key)

group_analysis$group <- cumsum(c(1, diff.Date(group_analysis$s_at)) >= 120)

group_analysis <- group_analysis %>%
  arrange(e_at) %>%
  arrange(route_key)

group_analysis$group_2 <- cumsum(c(1, diff.Date(group_analysis$e_at)) >= 120)

ga_total <- group_analysis %>%
  group_by(route_key, group, group_2) %>%
  tally(name = "no_total")

ga_casual <- group_analysis %>%
  filter(m_c == "casual") %>%
  group_by(route_key, group, group_2) %>%
  tally(name = "no_casual")

ga_member <- group_analysis %>%
  filter(m_c == "member") %>%
  group_by(route_key, group, group_2) %>%
  tally(name = "no_member")

ga <- full_join(ga_casual, ga_member, by = join_by(route_key, group, group_2))

ga <- left_join(ga, ga_total, by = join_by(route_key, group, group_2))

ga$group_key <- seq(1:nrow(ga))

ga_a <- ga %>%
  group_by(no_total) %>%
  summarise(count = sum(no_total))

ga_a$pct <- ((ga_a$count * ga_a$no_total) / 5723727) * 100

g_gaa <- ga_a %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = no_total, y = count, label = paste0(round(pct, 1), "%") )) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(title = "Proportionality of Different Group Sizes") +
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = .9), vjust = -0.5, size = 7)

Percentage of Casual trips that fall under this “Peak Season” umbrella

casual_trips <- trips %>%
  filter(m_c == "casual") %>%
  mutate("date" = as.Date(s_at, format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")) %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise("total" = n()) %>%
  mutate("season" = ifelse(date >= as.Date("01/06/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y") &
                             date < as.Date("01/09/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y"),
                           "Peak Season", "Off-Season"),
         "wd" = wday(date, week_start = 1)) %>%
  mutate("we" = ifelse(wd >= 6, T, F))




g_seasonal_usage <- casual_trips %>%
  group_by(season) %>%
  summarise("total" = sum(total)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = "", y = total/sum(total), fill = season)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#6DDFD5", "#9ED251")) +
  labs(title = "Proportion of Trips that Occur During Peak Season",
       fill = "Season") +
  geom_text(aes(label = c(paste0(round((total/sum(total))*100, 0), "%"))),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 20) +
  theme_void()

g_seasonal_usage

comparison <- casual_trips %>%
  mutate("season" = ifelse(date >= as.Date("01/06/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y") &
                             date < as.Date("01/09/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y"),
                           "Peak Season",
                           ifelse(date >= as.Date("01/09/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y") &
                                    date < as.Date("01/12/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y"),
                                  "Off-Season (Autumn)",
                                  ifelse(date >= as.Date("01/12/2022", format = "%d/%m/%Y") &
                                           date < as.Date("01/3/2023", format = "%d/%m/%Y"),
                                         "Off-Season (Winter)", "Off-Season (Spring)"))),
         "wd" = wday(date, week_start = 1)) %>%
  mutate("we" = ifelse(wd >= 5, T, F))

                                levels = c("Off-Season (Spring)", 
                                           "Off-Season (Winter)",
                                           "Off-Season (Autumn)", 
                                           "Peak Season"))
